Tesla's valuation is totally unmoored from reality, relying as it does on a dream of total auto industry domination. Europe may be the canary in the coal mine for Tesla, as its seemingly unassailable position has been overtaken by "dinosaur" OEMs. $TSLA $TSLAQ

10/

Consider Europe: 

While the European EV market grew 137% y-o-y in 2020, Tesla sales were down 10%. Even as VW claimed the top spot, Tesla fell to 3rd place in the region – a prospect many bulls claimed to be impossible not long ago. $TSLA $TSLAQ

9/

The market has priced in truly spectacular growth for Tesla. At more than four times Volkswagen's market capitalization, Tesla's current valuation implies nearly 40 million in annual sales – a tough ask for any automaker. $TSLA $TSLAQ

8/
https://t.co/lBe1VIFafo

One might contend that Tesla is priced for growth, while VW isn't. This is a popular bullish refrain. But this ignores the growth of rivals in the EV space. VW alone saw plug-in vehicle sales surge 195% in 2020 to 422,000 and BEV sales up 214% to 231,600. $TSLA $TSLAQ

7/

At $587 billion, Tesla's market cap dwarfs that of Volkswagen AG, which stands at just $137 billion. 

Yet VW sold approx. 9.3 million vehicles in 2020 compared to Tesla's 499,550. 

In other words, VW had 18.6x Tesla's, yet Tesla's valuation is still 4.3x. 

$TSLA $TSLAQ

6/

Tesla was an early mover and has been the best seller worldwide for years. Yet this status has come under serious – and intensifying – threat. As Tesla's recent experience in Europe amply demonstrates, the competition is no joke. $TSLA $TSLAQ

Of critical importance is the relationship of EVs to the overall automotive market, which is largely saturated. Thus EV market growth is actually growth of a submarket within the overall auto market – growth that's largely at the expense of the ICE submarket. $TSLA $TSLAQ
